{{education-stub}}

{{About|the American education movement||Free school (disambiguation){{!}}Free School}}
{{Students rights sidebar}}
The '''free school movement''', also known as the '''new schools''' or '''alternative schools movement''', was an American [[education reform]] [[Social movement|movement]] during the 1960s and early 1970s that sought to change the aims of formal schooling through alternative, [[Independent school|independent community schools]].

== Origins and influences ==

[[File:SummerhillSchool.jpg|thumb|Summerhill, the model for the first American free schools, pictured in 1993]] As disenchantment with social institutions spread with the [[Counterculture of the 1960s|1960s counterculture]], alternative schools sprouted outside the local public school system. Funded by tuition and philanthropic grants,{{r|Altenbaugh}} they were created by parents, teachers, and students in opposition to contemporaneous schooling practices across the United States and organized without central organization, usually small and grassroots with alternative curricula.{{r|Altenbaugh}} Their philosophical influence stemmed from the counterculture, [[A. S. Neill]] and [[Summerhill School|Summerhill]], [[child-centered learning|child-centered]] [[progressive education]] of the [[Progressive Era]], the [[Modern Schools]], and [[Freedom Schools]].{{r|Altenbaugh}} Influential voices within the movement included [[Paul Goodman]], [[Edgar Z. Friedenberg]], [[Herbert Kohl (educator)|Herb Kohl]], [[Jonathan Kozol]], and [[James Herndon (writer)|James Herndon]], with titles such as A. S. Neill's 1960 ''[[Summerhill (book)|Summerhill]]'', [[George Dennison]]'s 1969 ''[[The Lives of Children]]'', and Jonathan Kozol's 1972 ''Free Schools''.{{r|Altenbaugh}} The movement's transference of ideas was tracked through the ''New Schools Exchange'' and American Summerhill Society.{{r|Altenbaugh}}

The definition and scope of schools self-classified as "free schools" and their associated movement were never clearly delineated, and as such, there was a wide variation between schools.{{sfn|Graubard|1972c|p=1}} The movement did not subscribe to a single ideology, but its "free schools" tended to fall into the binaries of either utopian cultural withdrawal from external concerns, or built on the legacy of freedom schools with direct political address of social injustices.{{r|Altenbaugh}} This dicotomy was also seen in the type of students the school attracted with the aforementioned being of white, middle class students and the second usually poor, black, and inner-city.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barr|first=Robert D.|date=1973|title=Whatever Happened to the Free School Movement?|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/20373543|journal=The Phi Delta Kappan|volume=54|issue=7|pages=454–457}}</ref> Some schools practiced [[participatory democracies]] for self-governance.{{r|Altenbaugh}} The "free schools" movement was also known as the "new schools" or "alternative schools movement".{{sfn|Graubard|1972c|p=1}} Author Ron Miller defined the free school movement's principles as letting families choose for their children, and letting children learn at their own pace.{{r|HuffPo: BFS 2012}}

== Growth ==

Allen Graubard charted the growth of the free schools from 25 in 1967 to around 600 in 1972, with estimates of 200 created between 1971 and 1972.{{sfn|Graubard|1972c|p=1}} These schools had an average enrollment of 33 students.{{sfn|Graubard|1972c|p=1}} Almost all of the first American free schools were based on Summerhill and its associated book.{{sfn|Graubard|1972c|p=2}} Many of the schools were started in nontraditional locations, including parks, churches, and abandoned buildings.{{r|HuffPo: BFS 2012}}

The movement peaked in 1972 with hundreds of schools opened and public interest in [[open education]].{{r|HuffPo: BFS 2012}}

== Decline and legacy ==

The movement subsided with the rise of [[Conservatism in the United States#1970s|1970s conservatism]],{{r|Altenbaugh}} particularly due to the [[Nixon administration]]'s education policies.{{r|HuffPo: BFS 2012}}

''[[The Huffington Post]]'' wrote in 2012 that "the movement is revving up again", citing Education Revolution's listing of over 100 free schools in America. The schools are mostly private in America, and generally serve middle and upper-middle-class families. Author Ron Miller credits the rise of standardization with grassroots interest in alternative schools.{{r|HuffPo: BFS 2012}} [[CBS News]] reported in 2006 that the remaining free schools, while unknown in number, are "democratic", as the students share in the school's governance.{{r|CBS 2006}}

Education historian [[Diane Ravitch]] said in 2004 that these schools function best for students from educated families due to the free schools' emphasis on individual contribution.{{r|NYT 2004}} Victoria Goldman of ''The Manhattan Family Guide to Private Schools and Selective Public Schools'' and [[E. D. Hirsch, Jr.]] echoed similar thoughts, with Hirsch adding that "it doesn't work for children who haven't had those advantages."{{r|NYT 2006}} Ravitch believed that the free schools' values would conflict with predominant student testing trends.{{r|NYT 2004}}

